SAT VOCABULARY REFERENCE
396 SAT vocabulary words with definitions, synonyms, and example sentences

================================================================================

INTIMATION
Definition: an indirect suggestion
Synonyms: hint, indication, insinuation
Example: Mr. Brinford's intimation that he would soon pass away occurred when he began to discuss how to distribute his belongings among his children.

INTRACTABLE
Definition: difficult to manipulate, unmanageable
Synonyms: stubborn, unruly, obstinate
Example: There was no end in sight to the intractable conflict between the warring countries.

INTRANSIGENT
Definition: refusing to compromise, often on an extreme opinion
Synonyms: inflexible, uncompromising, stubborn
Example: The intransigent child said he would have 12 scoops of ice cream, or he would bang his head against the wall until his mother fainted from fear.

INTREPID
Definition: brave in the face of danger
Synonyms: fearless, courageous, bold
Example: After scaling a live volcano prior to its eruption, the explorer was praised for his intrepid attitude.

INUNDATE
Definition: to flood with abundance
Synonyms: overwhelm, swamp, deluge
Example: Because I am the star of a new sitcom, my fans are sure to inundate me with fan mail and praise.

INURE
Definition: to cause someone or something to become accustomed to a situation
Synonyms: harden, accustom, habituate
Example: Twenty years in the salt mines inured the man to the discomforts of dirt and grime.

INVECTIVE
Definition: an angry verbal attack
Synonyms: abuse, vituperation, diatribe
Example: My mother's irrational invective against the way I dress only made me decide to dye my hair green.

INVETERATE
Definition: stubbornly established by habit
Synonyms: habitual, chronic, confirmed
Example: I'm the first to admit that I'm an inveterate coffee drinker—I drink four cups a day.

INVIOLABLE
Definition: secure from assault
Synonyms: sacred, untouchable, impregnable
Example: Nobody was ever able to break into Batman's inviolable Batcave.

IRASCIBLE
Definition: easily angered
Synonyms: irritable, testy, short-tempered
Example: At the smallest provocation, my irascible cat will begin scratching and clawing.

IRIDESCENT
Definition: showing rainbow colors
Synonyms: shimmering, opalescent, lustrous
Example: The bride's large diamond ring was iridescent in the afternoon sun.

IRREVERENCE
Definition: disrespect
Synonyms: impiety, disrespect, blasphemy
Example: The irreverence displayed by the band that marched through the chapel disturbed many churchgoers.

IRREVOCABLE
Definition: incapable of being taken back
Synonyms: irreversible, permanent, final
Example: The Bill of Rights is an irrevocable part of American law.

JUBILANT
Definition: extremely joyful, happy
Synonyms: elated, exultant, ecstatic
Example: The crowd was jubilant when the firefighter carried the woman from the flaming building.

JUDICIOUS
Definition: having or exercising sound judgment
Synonyms: wise, prudent, sensible
Example: When the judicious king decided to compromise rather than send his army to its certain death, he was applauded.

JUXTAPOSITION
Definition: the act of placing two things next to each other for implicit comparison
Synonyms: proximity, contrast, comparison
Example: The interior designer admired my juxtaposition of the yellow couch and green table.

KNELL
Definition: the solemn sound of a bell, often indicating a death
Synonyms: toll, chime, death knell
Example: Echoing throughout our village, the funeral knell made the stormy day even more grim.

KUDOS
Definition: praise for an achievement
Synonyms: acclaim, praise, recognition
Example: After the performance, the reviewers gave the opera singer kudos for a job well done.

LACERATION
Definition: a cut, tear
Synonyms: wound, gash, incision
Example: Because he fell off his bike into a rosebush, the paperboy's skin was covered with lacerations.

LACONIC
Definition: terse in speech or writing
Synonyms: concise, brief, succinct
Example: The author's laconic style has won him many followers who dislike wordiness.

LANGUID
Definition: sluggish from fatigue or weakness
Synonyms: lethargic, listless, weak
Example: In the summer months, the great heat makes people languid and lazy.

LARCENY
Definition: obtaining another's property by theft or trickery
Synonyms: theft, robbery, stealing
Example: When my car was not where I had left it, I realized that I was a victim of larceny.

LARGESS
Definition: the generous giving of lavish gifts
Synonyms: generosity, munificence, bounty
Example: My boss demonstrated great largess by giving me a new car.

LATENT
Definition: hidden, but capable of being exposed
Synonyms: dormant, concealed, potential
Example: Sigmund's dream represented his latent paranoid obsession with other people's shoes.

LAUDATORY
Definition: expressing admiration or praise
Synonyms: complimentary, approving, praising
Example: Such laudatory comments are unusual from someone who is usually so reserved in his opinions.

LAVISH
Definition: given without limits; to give without limits
Synonyms: abundant, generous, profuse
Example: Because they had worked very hard, the performers appreciated the critic's lavish praise.

LEGERDEMAIN
Definition: deception, sleight-of-hand
Synonyms: trickery, deception, chicanery
Example: Smuggling the French plants through customs by claiming that they were fake was a remarkable bit of legerdemain.

LENIENT
Definition: demonstrating tolerance or gentleness
Synonyms: permissive, indulgent, forgiving
Example: Because Professor Oglethorpe allowed his students to choose their final grades, the other teachers believed that he was excessively lenient.

LETHARGIC
Definition: in a state of sluggishness or apathy
Synonyms: sluggish, listless, torpid
Example: When Jean Claude explained to his boss that he was lethargic and didn't feel like working that day, the boss fired him.

LIABILITY
Definition: something for which one is legally responsible, usually involving a disadvantage or risk; a handicap, burden
Synonyms: responsibility, burden, disadvantage
Example: The bungee-jumping tower was a great liability for the owners of the carnival.

LIBERTARIAN
Definition: advocating principles of liberty and free will
Synonyms: freedom-loving, democratic, individualistic
Example: The dissatisfied subjects overthrew the monarch and replaced him with a libertarian ruler who respected their democratic principles.

LICENTIOUS
Definition: displaying a lack of moral or legal restraints
Synonyms: immoral, dissolute, debauched
Example: Marilee has always been fascinated by the licentious private lives of politicians.

LIMPID
Definition: clear, transparent
Synonyms: clear, lucid, crystalline
Example: Mr. Johnson's limpid writing style greatly pleased readers who disliked complicated novels.

LINCHPIN
Definition: something that holds separate parts together
Synonyms: cornerstone, mainstay, keystone
Example: The linchpin in the prosecution's case was the hair from the defendant's head, which was found at the scene of the crime.

LITHE
Definition: graceful, flexible, supple
Synonyms: agile, limber, flexible
Example: Although the dancers were all outstanding, Jae Sun's control of her lithe body was particularly impressive.

LITIGANT
Definition: someone engaged in a lawsuit
Synonyms: plaintiff, defendant, party
Example: When the litigants began screaming at each other, Judge Koch ordered them to be silent.

LUCID
Definition: clear, easily understandable
Synonyms: clear, coherent, intelligible
Example: Because Guenevere's essay was so lucid, I only had to read it once to understand her reasoning.

LUMINOUS
Definition: brightly shining
Synonyms: radiant, glowing, bright
Example: The light of the luminous moon graced the shoulders of the beautiful maiden.

LURID
Definition: ghastly, sensational
Synonyms: shocking, gruesome, horrifying
Example: Gideon's story, in which he described a character torturing his sister's dolls, was judged too lurid to be printed in the school's literary magazine.

MAELSTROM
Definition: a destructive whirlpool which rapidly sucks in objects
Synonyms: whirlpool, vortex, chaos
Example: Little did the explorers know that as they turned the next bend of the calm river a vicious maelstrom would catch their boat.

MAGNANIMOUS
Definition: noble, generous
Synonyms: generous, noble, benevolent
Example: Although I had already broken most of her dishes, Jacqueline was magnanimous enough to continue letting me use them.

MALEDICTION
Definition: a curse
Synonyms: curse, imprecation, hex
Example: When I was arrested for speeding, I screamed maledictions against the policeman and the entire police department.

MALEVOLENT
Definition: wanting harm to befall others
Synonyms: malicious, spiteful, evil
Example: The malevolent old man sat in the park all day, tripping unsuspecting passersby with his cane.

MALLEABLE
Definition: capable of being shaped or transformed
Synonyms: pliable, flexible, adaptable
Example: Maximillian's political opinions were so malleable that anyone he talked to was able to change his mind instantly.

MANDATE
Definition: an authoritative command
Synonyms: order, directive, command
Example: In the Old Testament, God mandates that no one should steal.

MANIFEST
Definition: easily understandable, obvious; to show plainly
Synonyms: evident, apparent, clear
Example: When I wrote the wrong sum on the chalkboard, my mistake was so manifest that the entire class burst into laughter.

MANIFOLD
Definition: diverse, varied
Synonyms: varied, diverse, multiple
Example: The popularity of Dante's Inferno is partly due to the fact that the work allows for manifold interpretations.

MAUDLIN
Definition: weakly sentimental
Synonyms: sentimental, mawkish, mushy
Example: Although many people enjoy romantic comedies, I usually find them maudlin and shallow.

MAVERICK
Definition: an independent, nonconformist person
Synonyms: nonconformist, rebel, individualist
Example: Andreas is a real maverick and always does things his own way.

MAWKISH
Definition: characterized by sick sentimentality
Synonyms: sentimental, saccharine, cloying
Example: Although some nineteenth-century critics viewed Dickens's writing as mawkish, contemporary readers have found great emotional depth in his works.

MAXIM
Definition: a common saying expressing a principle of conduct
Synonyms: proverb, adage, saying
Example: Miss Manners's etiquette maxims are both entertaining and instructional.

MEAGER
Definition: deficient in size or quality
Synonyms: scanty, sparse, insufficient
Example: My meager portion of food did nothing to satisfy my appetite.

MEDLEY
Definition: a mixture of differing things
Synonyms: mixture, assortment, variety
Example: Susannah's wardrobe contained an astonishing medley of colors, from olive green to fluorescent pink.

MENDACIOUS
Definition: having a lying, false character
Synonyms: dishonest, deceitful, untruthful
Example: The mendacious content of the tabloid magazines is at least entertaining.

MERCURIAL
Definition: characterized by rapid change or temperamentality
Synonyms: volatile, unpredictable, capricious
Example: Though he was widely respected for his mathematical proofs, the mercurial genius was impossible to live with.

MERITORIOUS
Definition: worthy of esteem or reward
Synonyms: praiseworthy, commendable, laudable
Example: Manfred was given the congressional medal of honor for his meritorious actions.

METAMORPHOSIS
Definition: the change of form, shape, substance
Synonyms: transformation, change, conversion
Example: Winnifred went to the gym every day for a year and underwent a metamorphosis from a waiflike girl to an athletic woman.

METICULOUS
Definition: extremely careful with details
Synonyms: careful, thorough, precise
Example: The ornate needlework in the bride's gown was a product of meticulous handiwork.

MITIGATE
Definition: to make less violent, alleviate
Synonyms: lessen, alleviate, reduce
Example: When I had an awful sore throat, only warm tea would mitigate the pain.

MODERATE
Definition: not extreme; one who expresses moderate opinions
Synonyms: temperate, reasonable, restrained
Example: Luckily, the restaurant we chose had moderate prices; none of us have any money.

MODICUM
Definition: a small amount of something
Synonyms: bit, trace, iota
Example: Refusing to display even a modicum of sensitivity, Henrietta announced her boss's affair in front of the entire office.

MODULATE
Definition: to pass from one state to another, especially in music
Synonyms: adjust, regulate, vary
Example: The composer wrote a piece that modulated between minor and major keys.

MOLLIFY
Definition: to soften in temper
Synonyms: placate, appease, soothe
Example: The police officer mollified the angry woman by giving her a warning instead of a ticket.

MORASS
Definition: a wet swampy bog; figuratively, something that traps and confuses
Synonyms: quagmire, swamp, predicament
Example: When Theresa lost her job, she could not get out of her financial morass.

MORES
Definition: the moral attitudes and fixed customs of a group of people
Synonyms: customs, traditions, conventions
Example: Mores change over time; many things that were tolerated in 1975 are no longer seen as being socially acceptable.

MOROSE
Definition: gloomy or sullen
Synonyms: sullen, melancholy, gloomy
Example: Jason's morose nature made him very unpleasant to talk to.

MULTIFARIOUS
Definition: having great diversity or variety
Synonyms: diverse, varied, manifold
Example: This Swiss Army knife has multifarious functions and capabilities.

MUNDANE
Definition: concerned with the world rather than with heaven, commonplace
Synonyms: ordinary, commonplace, earthly
Example: He is more concerned with the mundane issues of day-to-day life than with spiritual topics.

MUNIFICENCE
Definition: generosity in giving
Synonyms: generosity, liberality, bounty
Example: The royal family's munificence made everyone else in their country rich.

MUTABLE
Definition: able to change
Synonyms: changeable, variable, inconstant
Example: Because fashion is so mutable, what is trendy today will look outdated in five years.

MYRIAD
Definition: consisting of a very great number
Synonyms: countless, innumerable, multitudinous
Example: It was difficult to decide what to do Friday night because the city presented us with myriad possibilities for fun.

NADIR
Definition: the lowest point of something
Synonyms: bottom, low point, depths
Example: My day was boring, but the nadir came when I accidentally spilled a bowl of spaghetti on my head.

NASCENT
Definition: in the process of being born or coming into existence
Synonyms: emerging, developing, budding
Example: Unfortunately, my brilliant paper was only in its nascent form on the morning that it was due.

NEBULOUS
Definition: vaguely defined, cloudy
Synonyms: vague, unclear, hazy
Example: The transition between governments meant that who was actually in charge was a nebulous matter.

NEFARIOUS
Definition: heinously villainous
Synonyms: wicked, evil, villainous
Example: Although Dr. Meanman's nefarious plot to melt the polar icecaps was terrifying, it was so impractical that nobody really worried about it.

NEGLIGENT
Definition: habitually careless, neglectful
Synonyms: careless, neglectful, remiss
Example: Jessie's grandfather called me a negligent fool after I left the door to his apartment unlocked even though there had been a recent string of robberies.

NEOPHYTE
Definition: someone who is young or inexperienced
Synonyms: beginner, novice, newcomer
Example: As a neophyte in the literary world, Malik had trouble finding a publisher for his first novel.

NOCTURNAL
Definition: relating to or occurring during the night
Synonyms: nighttime, night, nightly
Example: Jackie was a nocturnal person; she would study until dawn and sleep until the evening.

NOISOME
Definition: unpleasant, offensive, especially to the sense of smell
Synonyms: foul, offensive, noxious
Example: Nobody would enter the stalls until the horse's noisome leavings were taken away.

NOMADIC
Definition: wandering from place to place
Synonyms: wandering, itinerant, roving
Example: In the first six months after college, Jose led a nomadic life, living in New York, California, and Idaho.

NOMINAL
Definition: trifling, insignificant
Synonyms: minimal, token, insignificant
Example: Because he was moving the following week and needed to get rid of his furniture more than he needed money, Jordan sold everything for a nominal fee.

NONCHALANT
Definition: having a lack of concern, indifference
Synonyms: casual, indifferent, unconcerned
Example: Although deep down she was very angry, Marsha acted in a nonchalant manner when she found out that her best friend had used her clothing without asking.

NONDESCRIPT
Definition: lacking a distinctive character
Synonyms: ordinary, unremarkable, plain
Example: I was surprised when I saw the movie star in person because she looked nondescript.

NOTORIOUS
Definition: widely and unfavorably known
Synonyms: infamous, disreputable, scandalous
Example: Jacob was notorious for always arriving late at parties.

NOVICE
Definition: a beginner, someone without training or experience
Synonyms: beginner, neophyte, amateur
Example: Because we were all novices at yoga, our instructor decided to begin with the basics.

NOXIOUS
Definition: harmful, unwholesome
Synonyms: harmful, toxic, poisonous
Example: Environmentalists showed that the noxious weeds were destroying the insects' natural habitats.

NUANCE
Definition: a slight variation in meaning, tone, expression
Synonyms: subtlety, shade, distinction
Example: The nuances of the poem were not obvious to the casual reader, but the professor was able to point them out.

NURTURE
Definition: to assist the development of
Synonyms: foster, cultivate, nourish
Example: Although Serena had never watered the plant, which was about to die, Javier was able to nurture it back to life.

OBDURATE
Definition: unyielding to persuasion or moral influences
Synonyms: stubborn, inflexible, obstinate
Example: The obdurate old man refused to take pity on the kittens.

OBFUSCATE
Definition: to render incomprehensible
Synonyms: confuse, obscure, muddle
Example: The detective did not want to answer the newspaperman's questions, so he obfuscated the truth.

OBLIQUE
Definition: diverging from a straight line or course, not straightforward
Synonyms: indirect, evasive, slanted
Example: Martin's oblique language confused those who listened to him.

OBLIVIOUS
Definition: lacking consciousness or awareness of something
Synonyms: unaware, unconscious, heedless
Example: Oblivious to the burning smell emanating from the kitchen, my father did not notice that the rolls in the oven were burned until much too late.

OBSCURE
Definition: unclear, partially hidden
Synonyms: unclear, vague, indistinct
Example: Because he was standing in the shadows, his features were obscure.

OBSEQUIOUS
Definition: excessively compliant or submissive
Synonyms: servile, fawning, sycophantic
Example: Mark acted like Janet's servant, obeying her every request in an obsequious manner.

OBSOLETE
Definition: no longer used, out of date
Synonyms: outdated, antiquated, archaic
Example: With the inventions of tape decks and CDs, which both have better sound and are easier to use, eight-track players are now entirely obsolete.

OBSTINATE
Definition: not yielding easily, stubborn
Synonyms: stubborn, headstrong, unyielding
Example: The obstinate child refused to leave the store until his mother bought him a candy bar.

OBSTREPEROUS
Definition: noisy, unruly
Synonyms: boisterous, rowdy, unruly
Example: Billy's obstreperous behavior prompted the librarian to ask him to leave the reading room.

OBTUSE
Definition: lacking quickness of sensibility or intellect
Synonyms: dull, slow, dense
Example: Political opponents warned that the prime minister's obtuse approach to foreign policy would embroil the nation in mindless war.

ODIOUS
Definition: instilling hatred or intense displeasure
Synonyms: hateful, detestable, repugnant
Example: Mark was assigned the odious task of cleaning the cat's litter box.

OFFICIOUS
Definition: offering one's services when they are neither wanted nor needed
Synonyms: meddlesome, intrusive, interfering
Example: Brenda resented Allan's officious behavior when he selected colors that might best improve her artwork.

OMINOUS
Definition: foreboding or foreshadowing evil
Synonyms: threatening, menacing, sinister
Example: The fortuneteller's ominous words flashed through my mind as the hooded figure approached me in the alley.

ONEROUS
Definition: burdensome
Synonyms: burdensome, oppressive, taxing
Example: My parents lamented that the pleasures of living in a beautiful country estate no longer outweighed the onerous mortgage payments.

OPULENT
Definition: characterized by rich abundance verging on ostentation
Synonyms: luxurious, lavish, sumptuous
Example: The opulent furnishings of the dictator's private compound contrasted harshly with the meager accommodations of her subjects.

ORATION
Definition: a speech delivered in a formal or ceremonious manner
Synonyms: speech, address, discourse
Example: The prime minister was visibly shaken when the unruly parliament interrupted his oration about failed domestic policies.

ORNATE
Definition: highly elaborate, excessively decorated
Synonyms: elaborate, decorative, embellished
Example: The ornate styling of the new model of luxury car could not compensate for the poor quality of its motor.

ORTHODOX
Definition: conventional, conforming to established protocol
Synonyms: conventional, traditional, established
Example: The company's profits dwindled because the management pursued orthodox business policies that were incompatible with new industrial trends.

OSCILLATE
Definition: to sway from one side to the other
Synonyms: fluctuate, waver, vacillate
Example: My uncle oscillated between buying a station wagon to transport his family and buying a sports car to satisfy his boyhood fantasies.

OSTENSIBLE
Definition: appearing as such, seemingly
Synonyms: apparent, seeming, supposed
Example: Jack's ostensible reason for driving was that airfare was too expensive, but in reality, he was afraid of flying.

OSTENTATIOUS
Definition: excessively showy, glitzy
Synonyms: showy, flashy, pretentious
Example: On the palace tour, the guide focused on the ostentatious decorations and spoke little of the royal family's history.

OSTRACISM
Definition: exclusion from a group
Synonyms: exclusion, banishment, rejection
Example: Beth risked ostracism if her roommates discovered her flatulence.

PACIFIC
Definition: soothing
Synonyms: peaceful, calming, tranquil
Example: The chemistry professor's pacific demeanor helped the class remain calm after the experiment exploded.

PALATABLE
Definition: agreeable to the taste or sensibilities
Synonyms: acceptable, pleasant, agreeable
Example: Despite the unpleasant smell, the exotic cheese was quite palatable.

PALETTE
Definition: a range of colors or qualities
Synonyms: range, spectrum, variety
Example: The palette of colors utilized in the painting was equaled only by the range of intense emotions the piece evoked.

PALLIATE
Definition: to reduce the severity of
Synonyms: alleviate, ease, relieve
Example: The doctor trusted that the new medication would palliate her patient's discomfort.

PALLID
Definition: lacking color
Synonyms: pale, wan, ashen
Example: Dr. Van Helsing feared that Lucy's pallid complexion was due to an unexplained loss of blood.

PANACEA
Definition: a remedy for all ills or difficulties
Synonyms: cure-all, remedy, solution
Example: Doctors wish there was a single panacea for every disease, but sadly there is not.

PARADIGM
Definition: an example that is a perfect pattern or model
Synonyms: model, pattern, example
Example: Because the new SUV was so popular, it became the paradigm upon which all others were modeled.

PARADOX
Definition: an apparently contradictory statement that is perhaps true
Synonyms: contradiction, anomaly, inconsistency
Example: The diplomat refused to acknowledge the paradox that negotiating a peace treaty would demand more resources than waging war.

PARAGON
Definition: a model of excellence or perfection
Synonyms: model, exemplar, ideal
Example: The mythical Helen of Troy was considered a paragon of female beauty.

PARAMOUNT
Definition: greatest in importance, rank, character
Synonyms: supreme, foremost, primary
Example: It was paramount that the bomb squad disconnect the blue wire before removing the fuse.

PARIAH
Definition: an outcast
Synonyms: outcast, exile, outsider
Example: Following the discovery of his plagiarism, Professor Hurley was made a pariah in all academic circles.

PARODY
Definition: a satirical imitation
Synonyms: satire, mockery, caricature
Example: A hush fell over the classroom when the teacher returned to find Deborah acting out a parody of his teaching style.

PARSIMONY
Definition: frugality, stinginess
Synonyms: frugality, stinginess, thrift
Example: Many relatives believed that my aunt's wealth resulted from her parsimony.

PARTISAN
Definition: a follower, adherent
Synonyms: supporter, follower, adherent
Example: The king did not believe that his rival could round up enough partisans to overthrow the monarchy.

PATENT
Definition: readily seen or understood, clear
Synonyms: obvious, evident, clear
Example: The reason for Jim's abdominal pain was made patent after the doctor performed a sonogram.

PATHOLOGY
Definition: a deviation from the normal
Synonyms: abnormality, disease, disorder
Example: Dr. Hastings had difficulty identifying the precise nature of Brian's pathology.

PATHOS
Definition: an emotion of sympathy
Synonyms: pity, sympathy, compassion
Example: Martha filled with pathos upon discovering the scrawny, shivering kitten at her door.

PAUCITY
Definition: small in quantity
Synonyms: scarcity, shortage, dearth
Example: Gilbert lamented the paucity of twentieth century literature courses available at the college.

PEJORATIVE
Definition: derogatory, uncomplimentary
Synonyms: derogatory, disparaging, belittling
Example: The evening's headline news covered an international scandal caused by a pejorative statement the famous senator had made in reference to a foreign leader.

PELLUCID
Definition: easily intelligible, clear
Synonyms: clear, lucid, transparent
Example: Wishing his book to be pellucid to the common man, Albert Camus avoided using complicated grammar when composing The Stranger.

PENCHANT
Definition: a tendency, partiality, preference
Synonyms: inclination, liking, fondness
Example: Jill's dinner parties quickly became monotonous on account of her penchant for Mexican dishes.

PENITENT
Definition: remorseful, regretful
Synonyms: remorseful, repentant, contrite
Example: The jury's verdict may have been more lenient if the criminal had appeared penitent for his gruesome crimes.

PENULTIMATE
Definition: next to last
Synonyms: second-to-last, penultimate, next-to-last
Example: Having smoked the penultimate cigarette remaining in the pack, Cybil discarded the last cigarette and resolved to quit smoking.

PENURIOUS
Definition: miserly, stingy
Synonyms: stingy, miserly, cheap
Example: Stella complained that her husband's penurious ways made it impossible to live the lifestyle she felt she deserved.

PERFIDIOUS
Definition: disloyal, unfaithful
Synonyms: treacherous, disloyal, traitorous
Example: After the official was caught selling government secrets to enemy agents, he was executed for his perfidious ways.

PERFUNCTORY
Definition: showing little interest or enthusiasm
Synonyms: cursory, superficial, mechanical
Example: The radio broadcaster announced the news of the massacre in a surprisingly perfunctory manner.

PERMEATE
Definition: to spread throughout, saturate
Synonyms: pervade, penetrate, saturate
Example: Mrs. Huxtable was annoyed that the wet dog's odor had permeated the furniture's upholstery.

PERNICIOUS
Definition: extremely destructive or harmful
Synonyms: harmful, destructive, damaging
Example: The new government feared that the Communist sympathizers would have a pernicious influence on the nation's stability.

PERPLEX
Definition: to confuse
Synonyms: confuse, puzzle, bewilder
Example: Brad was perplexed by his girlfriend's suddenly distant manner.

PERSPICACITY
Definition: shrewdness, perceptiveness
Synonyms: insight, acumen, discernment
Example: The detective was too humble to acknowledge that his perspicacity was the reason for his professional success.

PERT
Definition: flippant, bold
Synonyms: lively, saucy, cheeky
Example: My parents forgave Sandra's pert humor at the dinner table because it had been so long since they had last seen her.

PERTINACIOUS
Definition: stubbornly persistent
Synonyms: persistent, tenacious, dogged
Example: Harry's parents were frustrated with his pertinacious insistence that a monster lived in his closet.

PERUSAL
Definition: a careful examination, review
Synonyms: examination, study, scrutiny
Example: The actor agreed to accept the role after a two-month perusal of the movie script.

PERVASIVE
Definition: having the tendency to spread throughout
Synonyms: widespread, prevalent, ubiquitous
Example: Stepping off the plane in Havana, I recognized the pervasive odor of sugar cane fields on fire.

PETULANCE
Definition: rudeness, irritability
Synonyms: irritability, peevishness, testiness
Example: The Nanny resigned after she could no longer tolerate the child's petulance.

PHILANTHROPIC
Definition: charitable, giving
Synonyms: charitable, benevolent, generous
Example: Many people felt that the billionaire's decision to donate her fortune to house the homeless was the ultimate philanthropic act.

PHLEGMATIC
Definition: uninterested, unresponsive
Synonyms: apathetic, sluggish, unemotional
Example: Monique feared her dog was ill after the animal's phlegmatic response to his favorite chew toy.

PILLAGE
Definition: to seize or plunder, especially in war
Synonyms: plunder, loot, ransack
Example: Invading enemy soldiers pillaged the homes scattered along the country's border.

PINNACLE
Definition: the highest point
Synonyms: peak, summit, zenith
Example: Book reviewers declared that the author's new novel was extraordinary and probably the pinnacle of Western literature.

PITHY
Definition: concisely meaningful
Synonyms: concise, terse, succinct
Example: My father's long-winded explanation was a stark contrast to his usually pithy statements.

PITTANCE
Definition: a very small amount, especially relating to money
Synonyms: trifle, peanuts, small amount
Example: Josh complained that he was paid a pittance for the great amount of work he did at the firm.

PLACATE
Definition: to ease the anger of, soothe
Synonyms: appease, pacify, mollify
Example: The man purchased a lollipop to placate his irritable son.

PLACID
Definition: calm, peaceful
Synonyms: calm, peaceful, tranquil
Example: The placid lake surface was as smooth as glass.

PLATITUDE
Definition: an uninspired remark, cliché
Synonyms: cliché, truism, banality
