Example: The surrogate carried the child to term for its biological parents.

SWARTHY
Definition: of dark color or complexion
Synonyms: dark, dusky, tanned
Example: When he got drunk, Robinson's white skin became rather swarthy.

SYCOPHANT
Definition: one who flatters for self-gain
Synonyms: flatterer, toady, yes-man
Example: Some see the people in the cabinet as the president's closest advisors, but others see them as sycophants.

TACIT
Definition: expressed without words
Synonyms: implicit, unspoken, understood
Example: I interpreted my parents' refusal to talk as a tacit acceptance of my request.

TACITURN
Definition: not inclined to talk
Synonyms: reserved, reticent, quiet
Example: Though Jane never seems to stop talking, her brother is quite taciturn.

TANGENTIAL
Definition: incidental, peripheral, divergent
Synonyms: irrelevant, peripheral, digressive
Example: I tried to discuss my salary, but the boss kept veering off into tangential topics.

TANTAMOUNT
Definition: equivalent in value or significance
Synonyms: equivalent, equal, same
Example: When it comes to sports, fearing your opponent is tantamount to losing.

TEDIOUS
Definition: dull, boring
Synonyms: boring, monotonous, tiresome
Example: As time passed and the history professor continued to drone on and on, the lecture became increasingly tedious.

TEMERITY
Definition: audacity, recklessness
Synonyms: boldness, audacity, nerve
Example: Tom and Huck entered the scary cave armed with nothing but their own temerity.

TEMPERANCE
Definition: moderation in action or thought
Synonyms: moderation, restraint, self-control
Example: Maintaining temperance will ensure that you are able to think rationally and objectively.

TENABLE
Definition: able to be defended or maintained
Synonyms: defensible, justifiable, reasonable
Example: The department heads tore down the arguments in other people's theses, but Johari's work proved to be quite tenable.

TENUOUS
Definition: having little substance or strength
Synonyms: weak, flimsy, fragile
Example: Your argument is very tenuous, since it relies so much on speculation and hearsay.

TERRESTRIAL
Definition: relating to the land
Synonyms: earthly, land-based, worldly
Example: Elephants are terrestrial animals.

TIMOROUS
Definition: timid, fearful
Synonyms: timid, fearful, shy
Example: When dealing with the unknown, timorous Tallulah almost always broke into tears.

TIRADE
Definition: a long speech marked by harsh or biting language
Synonyms: diatribe, rant, harangue
Example: Every time Jessica was late, her boyfriend went into a long tirade about punctuality.

TOADY
Definition: one who flatters in the hope of gaining favors
Synonyms: sycophant, flatterer, brown-noser
Example: The other kids referred to the teacher's pet as the Tenth Grade Toady.

TOME
Definition: a large book
Synonyms: volume, book, work
Example: In college, I used to carry around an anatomy book that was the heaviest tome in my bag.

TORPID
Definition: lethargic, dormant, lacking motion
Synonyms: sluggish, lethargic, inactive
Example: The torpid whale floated, wallowing in the water for hours.

TORRID
Definition: giving off intense heat, passionate
Synonyms: hot, scorching, passionate
Example: I didn't want to witness the neighbor's torrid affair through the window.

TORTUOUS
Definition: winding
Synonyms: winding, twisting, serpentine
Example: The scary thing about driving in mountains are the narrow, tortuous roads.

TRACTABLE
Definition: easily controlled
Synonyms: manageable, compliant, docile
Example: The horse was so tractable, Myra didn't even need a bridle.

TRANQUIL
Definition: calm
Synonyms: peaceful, serene, calm
Example: There is a time of night when nothing moves and everything is tranquil.

TRANSGRESS
Definition: to violate, go over a limit
Synonyms: violate, breach, overstep
Example: The criminal's actions transgressed morality and human decency.

TRANSIENT
Definition: passing through briefly; passing into and out of existence
Synonyms: temporary, fleeting, ephemeral
Example: Because virtually everyone in Palm Beach is a tourist, the population of the town is quite transient.

TRANSMUTE
Definition: to change or alter in form
Synonyms: transform, convert, change
Example: Ancient alchemists believed that it was possible to transmute lead into gold.

TRAVESTY
Definition: a grossly inferior imitation
Synonyms: mockery, parody, farce
Example: According to the school newspaper's merciless theater critic, Pacific Coast High's rendition of the musical Oklahoma was a travesty of the original.

TREMULOUS
Definition: fearful
Synonyms: trembling, shaky, fearful
Example: I always feel a trifle tremulous when walking through a graveyard.

TRENCHANT
Definition: effective, articulate, clear-cut
Synonyms: incisive, sharp, effective
Example: The directions that accompanied my new cell phone were trenchant and easy to follow.

TREPIDATION
Definition: fear, apprehension
Synonyms: fear, anxiety, apprehension
Example: Feeling great trepidation, Anya refused to jump into the pool because she thought she saw a shark in it.

TRITE
Definition: not original, overused
Synonyms: banal, clichéd, hackneyed
Example: Keith thought of himself as being very learned, but everyone else thought he was trite because his observations about the world were always the same as David Letterman's.

TRUCULENT
Definition: ready to fight, cruel
Synonyms: aggressive, belligerent, hostile
Example: This club doesn't really attract the dangerous types, so why was that bouncer being so truculent?

TRUNCATE
Definition: to shorten by cutting off
Synonyms: shorten, abbreviate, cut
Example: After winning the derby, the jockey truncated the long speech he had planned and thanked only his mom and his horse.

TURGID
Definition: swollen, excessively embellished in style or language
Synonyms: pompous, bombastic, inflated
Example: The haughty writer did not realize how we all really felt about his turgid prose.

TURPITUDE
Definition: depravity, moral corruption
Synonyms: wickedness, depravity, immorality
Example: Sir Marcus's chivalry often contrasted with the turpitude he exhibited with the ladies at the tavern.

UBIQUITOUS
Definition: existing everywhere, widespread
Synonyms: omnipresent, pervasive, everywhere
Example: It seems that everyone in the United States has a television. The technology is ubiquitous here.

UMBRAGE
Definition: resentment, offense
Synonyms: offense, resentment, displeasure
Example: He called me a lily-livered coward, and I took umbrage at the insult.

UNCANNY
Definition: of supernatural character or origin
Synonyms: eerie, mysterious, strange
Example: Luka had an uncanny ability to know exactly what other people were thinking.

UNCTUOUS
Definition: smooth or greasy in texture, appearance, manner
Synonyms: oily, smarmy, ingratiating
Example: The unctuous receptionist seemed untrustworthy, as if she was only being helpful because she thought we might give her a big tip.

UNDULATE
Definition: to move in waves
Synonyms: wave, ripple, fluctuate
Example: As the storm began to brew, the placid ocean began to undulate to an increasing degree.

UPBRAID
Definition: to criticize or scold severely
Synonyms: scold, reprimand, rebuke
Example: The last thing Lindsay wanted was for Lisa to upbraid her again about missing the rent payment.

USURP
Definition: to seize by force, take possession of without right
Synonyms: seize, take over, commandeer
Example: The rogue army general tried to usurp control of the government, but he failed because most of the army backed the legally elected president.

UTILITARIAN
Definition: relating to or aiming at usefulness
Synonyms: practical, functional, useful
Example: The beautiful, fragile vase couldn't hold flowers or serve any other utilitarian purpose.

UTOPIA
Definition: an imaginary and remote place of perfection
Synonyms: paradise, ideal place, heaven
Example: Everyone in the world wants to live in a utopia, but no one can agree how to go about building one.

VACILLATE
Definition: to fluctuate, hesitate
Synonyms: waver, fluctuate, hesitate
Example: I prefer a definite answer, but my boss kept vacillating between the distinct options available to us.

VACUOUS
Definition: lack of content or ideas, stupid
Synonyms: empty, mindless, inane
Example: Beyonce realized that the lyrics she had just penned were completely vacuous and tried to add more substance.

VALIDATE
Definition: to confirm, support, corroborate
Synonyms: confirm, verify, authenticate
Example: Yoko's chemistry lab partner was asleep during the experiment and could not validate the accuracy of her methods.

VAPID
Definition: lacking liveliness, dull
Synonyms: dull, insipid, bland
Example: The professor's comments about the poem were surprisingly vapid and dull.

VARIEGATED
Definition: diversified, distinctly marked
Synonyms: varied, diverse, multicolored
Example: Each wire in the engineering exam was variegated by color so that the students could figure out which one was which.

VEHEMENTLY
Definition: marked by intense force or emotion
Synonyms: forcefully, passionately, intensely
Example: The candidate vehemently opposed cutting back on Social Security funding.

VENEER
Definition: a superficial or deceptively attractive appearance, façade
Synonyms: facade, surface, appearance
Example: Thanks to her Chanel makeup, Shannen was able to maintain a veneer of perfection that hid the flaws underneath.

VENERABLE
Definition: deserving of respect because of age or achievement
Synonyms: respected, revered, esteemed
Example: The venerable Supreme Court justice had made several key rulings in landmark cases throughout the years.

VENERATE
Definition: to regard with respect or to honor
Synonyms: revere, respect, honor
Example: The tribute to John Lennon sought to venerate his music, his words, and his legend.

VERACITY
Definition: truthfulness, accuracy
Synonyms: truthfulness, accuracy, honesty
Example: With several agencies regulating the reports, it was difficult for Latifah to argue against its veracity.

VERBOSE
Definition: wordy, impaired by wordiness
Synonyms: wordy, long-winded, prolix
Example: It took the verbose teacher two hours to explain the topic, while it should have taken only fifteen minutes.

VERDANT
Definition: green in tint or color
Synonyms: green, lush, flourishing
Example: The verdant leaves on the trees made the world look emerald.

VESTIGE
Definition: a mark or trace of something lost or vanished
Synonyms: trace, remnant, relic
Example: Do you know if the Mexican tortilla is a vestige of some form of Aztec corn-based flat bread?

VEX
Definition: to confuse or annoy
Synonyms: annoy, irritate, frustrate
Example: My little brother vexes me by poking me in the ribs for hours on end.

VICARIOUS
Definition: experiencing through another
Synonyms: indirect, secondhand, substituted
Example: All of my lame friends learned to be social through vicarious involvement in my amazing experiences.

VICISSITUDE
Definition: event that occurs by chance
Synonyms: change, variation, fluctuation
Example: The vicissitudes of daily life prevent me from predicting what might happen from one day to the next.

VIGILANT
Definition: watchful, alert
Synonyms: watchful, alert, attentive
Example: The guards remained vigilant throughout the night, but the enemy never launched the expected attack.

VILIFY
Definition: to lower in importance, defame
Synonyms: defame, slander, malign
Example: After the Watergate scandal, almost any story written about President Nixon sought to vilify him and criticize his behavior.

VINDICATE
Definition: to avenge; to free from allegation; to set free
Synonyms: exonerate, clear, absolve
Example: The attorney had no chance of vindicating the defendant with all of the strong evidence presented by the state.

VINDICTIVE
Definition: vengeful
Synonyms: vengeful, spiteful, revengeful
Example: The vindictive madman seeks to exact vengeance for any insult that he perceives is directed at him, no matter how small.

VIRTUOSO
Definition: one who excels in an art; a highly skilled musical performer
Synonyms: expert, master, prodigy
Example: Even though Lydia has studied piano for many years, she's only average at it. She's no virtuoso, that's for sure.

VISCOUS
Definition: not free flowing, syrupy
Synonyms: thick, sticky, syrupy
Example: The viscous syrup took three minutes to pour out of the bottle.

VITRIOLIC
Definition: having a caustic quality
Synonyms: bitter, scathing, caustic
Example: When angry, the woman would spew vitriolic insults.

VITUPERATE
Definition: to berate
Synonyms: berate, scold, rebuke
Example: Jack ran away as soon as his father found out, knowing he would be vituperated for his unseemly behavior.

VIVACIOUS
Definition: lively, sprightly
Synonyms: lively, animated, spirited
Example: The vivacious clown makes all of the children laugh and giggle with his friendly antics.

VOCATION
Definition: the work in which someone is employed, profession
Synonyms: profession, occupation, calling
Example: After growing tired of the superficial world of high-fashion, Edwina decided to devote herself to a new vocation: social work.

VOCIFEROUS
Definition: loud, boisterous
Synonyms: loud, clamorous, vehement
Example: I'm tired of his vociferous whining so I'm breaking up with him.

WALLOW
Definition: to roll oneself indolently; to become or remain helpless
Synonyms: indulge, luxuriate, revel
Example: My roommate can't get over her breakup with her boyfriend and now just wallows in self-pity.

WANE
Definition: to decrease in size, dwindle
Synonyms: decline, diminish, decrease
Example: Don't be so afraid of his wrath because his influence with the president is already beginning to wane.

WANTON
Definition: undisciplined, lewd, lustful
Synonyms: reckless, unrestrained, wild
Example: Vicky's wanton demeanor often made the frat guys next door very excited.

WHIMSICAL
Definition: fanciful, full of whims
Synonyms: playful, fanciful, capricious
Example: The whimsical little girl liked to pretend that she was an elvin princess.

WILY
Definition: crafty, sly
Synonyms: cunning, crafty, shrewd
Example: Though they were not the strongest of the Thundercats, wily Kit and Kat were definitely the most clever and full of tricks.

WINSOME
Definition: charming, pleasing
Synonyms: charming, appealing, engaging
Example: After such a long, frustrating day, I was grateful for Chris's winsome attitude and childish naivete.

WISTFUL
Definition: full of yearning; musingly sad
Synonyms: yearning, nostalgic, melancholy
Example: Since her pet rabbit died, Edda missed it terribly and sat around wistful all day long.

WIZENED
Definition: dry, shrunken, wrinkled
Synonyms: shriveled, withered, wrinkled
Example: Agatha's grandmother, Stephanie, had the most wizened countenance, full of leathery wrinkles.

WRATH
Definition: vengeful anger, punishment
Synonyms: anger, rage, fury
Example: Did you really want to incur her wrath when she is known for inflicting the worst punishments legally possible?

YOKE
Definition: to join, link
Synonyms: join, unite, connect
Example: We yoked together the logs by tying a string around them.

ZEALOUS
Definition: fervent, filled with eagerness in pursuit of something
Synonyms: enthusiastic, fervent, passionate
Example: If he were any more zealous about getting his promotion, he'd practically live at the office.

ZENITH
Definition: the highest point, culminating point
Synonyms: peak, apex, summit
Example: I was too nice to tell Nelly that she had reached the absolute zenith of her career with that one hit of hers.

ZEPHYR
Definition: a gentle breeze
Synonyms: breeze, wind, draft
Example: If not for the zephyrs that were blowing and cooling us, our room would've been unbearably hot.

